  <introduction>
    <p>
      Introduction goes here.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        Regions in the complex plane:
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              Circle: <m>|z-z_{0}|=r</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Disk: <m>|z-z_{0}|&#x3C;r</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Half planes: <m>\Real z>a</m>, <m>\Imag z\le b</m>, etc
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Annulus: <m>r_{1}\le |z-z_{0}|\le r_{2}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        We can visualize complex functions by considering what they do to particular regions of the complex plane.
        This is just like what we did with the Jacobian section!
      </p>

      <p>
        Example: What does <m>f(z)=z^{2}</m> do? We can expand it out and get:
        <me>
          f(z)=(x+\ii y)^{2}=(x^{2}-y^{2})+\ii(2xy)
        </me>
        So we can view this as the transformation
        <me>
          (x,y)\mapsto(x^{2}-y^{2},2xy)\text{.}
        </me>
        The Jacobian determinant of this matrix is
        <me>
          \bv J=\begin{bmatrix}2x&#x26;-2y\\ 2y&#x26;2x\end{bmatrix}
        </me>
        and the determinant is <m>4(x^{2}+y^{2})</m>.
        This shows how the lengths of small boxes will be scaled.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Parametric curves in the complex plane
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              Line (segment, ray): <m>z(t)=z_{0}(1-t)+z_{1}t</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Circle: <m>z(t)=z_{0}+r(\cos t+\ii\sin t)=z_{0}+r\ee^{\ii t}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
        Image of curve: If <m>w=f(z)</m>, then <m>w(t)=f(z(t))</m>.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Domain coloring: Let the input be the point on the complex plane, and let the output be how we color it.
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              Lightness = modulus (black = <m>0</m>, full color = <m>1</m>, white = <m>\infty</m>)
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Hue = argument (red = <m>0</m>, lime = <m>\uppi/2</m>, cyan = <m>\uppi</m>, purple = <m>3\uppi/2</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
        Based on this, we can tell where the zeros are because (1) the colors approach black, and (2) the colors will cycle around the points.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</section>
